<br>
Anyway, so i go on this pickup nagafen raid.  No offense to those running it, but it was kinda unorganized.  A lot of people sent tells to me complaining about this.  Now, personally I've tried running my own pickup raids before, and that is the reason I've sworn it off.  I hate trying to round up people, I hate trying to get them to listen, I hate trying to get them to stop their damn bitching, I hate having to explain the same simple rules (ie., when doing vox, don't push giants into the wall) over, and over, every single raid, and having people ignore them.<br>
<br>
In essence, I hate leading pickup raids, because of the general stupidity apparent in groups of people.  You know how when you get a group of people together, the larger the group, the lower the average intelligence becomes?  It doesn't matter how smart everyone is.  You could have 5,000 genius' all standing around, and I guaruntee if you tell them all to do something, they'll fuck it up.<br>
<br>
Alright, so, I get on this raid, and I speak to one of the people in charge.  I asked if they could use me (they had no bards there), and this person said yes.  I then said that if I'm not allowed on cloak of flames, since it's the only item i can really use that i'd be allowed on, that they would need to find another bard.<br>
<br>
Personally I don't think it was rude of me to make this stipulation.  First of all, a bard is on an even keel, if not in some situations better off than paladins, and perhaps one or two other melee classes, all of whom are allowed to roll on dragon haste items.<br>
<br>
For those who aren't aware, dragon haste items have been restricted to all melee except bard, at least as long as I've been raiding dragons, and probably a lot longer.<br>
<br>
However, I've always felt, as have a lot of bards, that this rule was pretty lame.  I've been allowed on cloak of flames before, and before I got my epic, I always refused because I wasn't a melee bard.  Before obtaining my epic, I strictly used instruments when fighting.  Therefore I didn't think it would be fair that I random on the cloak when someone else would make better use of it.<br>
<br>
However, not only are there bards out there who *DO* melee, there are bards such as myself who do melee, who have their epic.<br>
<br>
The bard epic procs a group-wide 55% haste that stacks with haste items, and though the haste component doesn't stack, it will stick to someone who has most other hastes on.  The reason for it, is that it has a direct +30 atk increase, +30 str (which adds to atk even more), and I believe it may have one or two other stat increases.<br>
<br>
Now, if this were a guild event, I would more than likely pass in favor of warriors and monks, and would expect other paladins, rogues, rangers, and SK's to do so as well.  Rangers and rogues get equipment haste better than the cloak on their epic, and warriors/monks would do more damage than any of the other melee classes if they were to get the cloak of flames.<br>
<br>
However, be'n that this is a pickup raid, I have the interests of myself and my guild in mind.  Yes, my damage input increases if I have cloak of flames.  However, the more I swing my weapon, the more chances it has of procing.  The buff that it procs lasts 2.5 minutes, which means either we need to have constant pulls on raids to keep the haste up, or I need a lot of dex &amp; existing haste to keep my group hasted.<br>
<br>
If i can keep my group hasted consistently, that saves the enchanters and shamans 4 people they don't need to buff with haste every 20-30 minutes, which saves mana, which will allow us to have less downtime, etc.  When we're fighting large encounters that need the best haste (ie., a dragon, maestro of rancor, etc), of course we'd want enc haste.  However, fighting average things in PoH, The Hole, etc, 55% haste that is free is going to help the raid out more than an enc spending mana to haste people.<br>
<br>
Now, you could say 'what if the enc's have their epic?  That's a 30 minute 60% haste'.  True, but currently my guild has no epic'ed enchanters, though we're working on it.  However, they won't need to worry about who does and doesn't have haste up any longer to make sure they are hasting them, if I'm able to facilitate the need.  Basically, as I've stated before to other people, bards are about efficiency.  If I can make my group more efficient (thereby making the raid more efficient) with a haste item, then why not?<br>
<br>
Now, back on topic.  I go on this raid, and tell them I won't join if I'm not allowed on the cloak.  The person leading it agrees, and I explain it to everyone when we're in the chat room after buffing.  So here I've contributed the strategy they needed (nagafen ended up warping to his spawn point, I honestly think that without the information that I imparted to them, however, they would have lost ... not to mention half the raid was buffed improperly.  Someone gave too many buffs before I could stop them, and resist magic and fire wasn't landing on a lot of people ... some of which were in my group, who received my bard MR / FR buffs that probably helped a LOT with keeping them from being feared / flamed easily)<br>
<br>
So, suddenly i have a bunch of people bitching at me, the ONLY bard on the raid, who wanted in on the cloak.  Out of 25 other melee's (26 including myself), they were complaining.  We then get done killing the dragon, and there were some casters who were very upset they aren't allowed in on the random.<br>
<br>
Now, I stated what items go to what classes in chat, and they agreed to continue.  I told them they could leave if they like, because it's not going to change, and they stayed, therefore they agreed.<br>
<br>
So now here people are calling me, tim, and other people present greedy ... why, because we weren't going to let some necromancer roll on an item he'd have sold in ebay commons.<br>
<br>
So I ask you for your opinions everyone ... I promise I won't flame your opinion (however I will respond with reasons for why I think your wrong), and I would hope no one else will either, if you disagree with my point of view ... what do you think should happen on pickup raids?<br>
<br>
Here we're trying to serve the greater good by giving the items to someone who will directly use them, and not someone who'll just go hawk it ... and some greedy necro starts whining about the hp/ac/dex on it that he couldn't give a rats ass about on any other item.<br>
<br>
What would you do, if you were leading the raid?<br>
<br>
